  faqs={[
    { question: 'Should I put on compression socks before transferring to my wheelchair, or after I am seated?', answer: 'Use the safest surface where you can reach your foot without rushing, dragging skin, or improvising a transfer. Some wheelchair users do better putting socks on in bed before transferring. Others do better once seated in the chair. The deciding factor is control, not a universal best location. If a transfer is involved, set up the sequence before movement, lock wheelchair brakes, and move footrests out of the way. If you cannot use at least one leg during a transfer, or if the transfer feels unsafe, consult your healthcare provider. After the sock is on, check the heel, cuff, seams, and any fabric touching footplates, calf supports, braces, or leg-rest hardware. The right location is the one that lets you finish the sock smoothly and still control the rest of the routine.' },
    { question: 'Where should the sock cuff sit if my wheelchair has footplates, calf supports, or leg rests?', answer: 'There is no single cuff location that works for every wheelchair setup. Use a fit-and-friction check instead of forcing a fixed height rule. After donning, look at where the sock contacts your footplates, calf supports, leg rests, braces, shoe edges, and straps. Smooth wrinkles. Check that the heel pocket is seated. Make sure the cuff is not rolled, folded, or trapped against a hard edge if you can reposition it comfortably. This is especially important if sensation is reduced, because a friction spot may not feel obvious in the moment. If you notice persistent redness, blistering, skin breakdown, or a new mark you cannot feel clearly, consult your healthcare provider. Compression socks should sit smoothly before your wheelchair hardware, shoes, or braces turn a small wrinkle into a repeat contact point.' },
    { question: 'Is it safe to stand briefly with my walker to finish putting on the sock?', answer: 'Stand briefly only if you are stable, cleared for that movement, and using the walker correctly. Put most of the sock on while seated first: toes seated, heel aligned, ankle smoothed, and cuff mostly up. If you need to stand for a final cuff adjustment, rise from the chair using armrests or handrails, not by pulling on or tilting the walker. Keep all walker tips or wheels grounded, lock brakes if your walker has them, and wait until you are steady before touching the sock. The adjustment should be small. Do not turn standing into the main donning method. Sit back down for detailed smoothing and to check wrinkles behind the calf. If standing creates balance risk, use a seated-only method, caregiver help, or OT guidance instead.' },
    { question: 'What about higher mmHg compression, is it better for people who sit all day?', answer: 'Higher mmHg compression is not automatically better for people who sit all day. Compression level selection belongs with your product instructions, the Compression 101 guide, and provider guidance when your condition requires it. AccessAble labels are 8-15 mmHg (Gentle Wellness), 15-20 mmHg (Everyday Relief), 20-30 mmHg (Medical Support), and 30-40 mmHg (Firm Medical). This article is about the mechanics of putting socks on with a wheelchair, walker, or cane. From a donning standpoint, higher compression can require more care because the sock may be harder to clear over the heel and ankle and harder to smooth without wrinkles. If you are unsure which level fits your needs, or if you have skin changes, reduced sensation, swelling that concerns you, or post-op instructions, consult your healthcare provider.' },
    { question: 'Are sock aids or donning devices worth trying?', answer: 'Sock aids or donning devices are worth trying when reach, grip, or leverage is the limiting factor. They are not a universal fix. A 2015 study in an older adult population with severe chronic venous insufficiency found that donning devices improved successful stocking application, but success depended on the device and the person using it (Sippel et al., 2015). That matters for mobility-aid users because the barrier may be different from person to person. One user may need a frame-style donning device. Another may need a foot slip, loops, a reacher, caregiver help, or an adaptive sock opening. Test the device in the place you actually dress: bed, wheelchair, firm chair, or edge of bed. If the device creates a transfer risk, skin drag, or a setup you cannot repeat, it is not the right solution for that routine.' },
    { question: 'My caregiver helps me put my socks on. Is that OK, or should I keep trying alone?', answer: 'Caregiver help is OK when it makes the routine safer, smoother, or more repeatable. Sock donning is an activity of daily living, and assistance with dressing is a legitimate part of mobility-aid routines. The goal is to make the help specific instead of vague. Decide who positions the leg, who starts the toe, who checks the heel, who pulls the cuff, and who checks contact against footplates, braces, shoes, or leg rests after the sock is on. If the caregiver is pulling too hard, rushing, or leaving wrinkles, the process needs adjustment. An OT can help train the sequence and recommend adaptive equipment or safer positioning. There is no extra credit for doing the whole task alone if the mechanics require another set of hands.' },
    { question: 'What if I had a recent hip replacement and use a walker, are the donning steps different?', answer: 'Yes, recent hip replacement instructions can change the safest donning posture. Some post-op instructions limit bending forward, crossing the legs, twisting, or dressing while standing. Those rules matter more than a generic sock sequence. Use the instructions from your surgeon, therapist, discharge plan, or home-health team first. A sock aid, reacher, long-handled device, caregiver assist, or seated-only setup may be safer than bending toward the foot. If you stand briefly with a walker, stand from the chair using armrests or handrails, wait until steady, and make only the smallest final adjustment. Do not pull on the walker to rise. This is exactly where personal precautions matter. If you are unsure whether a movement violates your precautions, consult your healthcare provider before using that donning position.' },
