  <p>Putting on compression socks with a mobility aid is a different task. I am Cody Coffey, founder of AccessAble, not a clinician. After a C4 incomplete spinal cord injury in December 2023, I spent four months in the hospital relying on staff to put my socks on, came home walking with a walker and my wife doing most of the donning, and worked back to doing it myself. I know how quickly a simple sock can become a full setup problem.</p>

  <h2>Why putting on compression socks is harder with a mobility aid</h2>

  <p>Compression socks are supposed to grip the leg. Graduated compression means the pressure is greatest around the ankle and decreases as the sock moves up the leg, which is why the heel and ankle are usually the hardest parts to clear. Researchers writing in CMAJ described noncompliance with graduated compression stockings in the 30% to 65% range, with difficulty donning included among the cited reasons (NCBI, 2014).</p>

  <p>That matters because mobility-aid users often cannot rely on the usual standing sequence. A person standing at the edge of a bed can brace a foot on the floor, hinge forward, and use bodyweight for leverage. A wheelchair user, walker user, or cane user may need to protect balance, keep one hand available for support, or work around footplates, braces, calf supports, and leg rests.</p>

  <p>This article is about putting on compression socks when they are already appropriate for you. Compression socks may help ease leg discomfort during prolonged sitting or limited mobility, but choosing a compression level (mmHg) belongs in the <a href="/learn/compression-101">Compression 101 guide</a>, not in this donning sequence.</p>

  <p>The better question is mechanical: Where can you reach your foot without rushing, twisting, dragging skin, or gambling with balance? That answer changes by device.</p>

  <h2>Putting on compression socks from a wheelchair</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Choose the safest reach position before the sock comes out.</strong> Some wheelchair users put socks on in bed before transferring. Others do it from the chair. Use the stable surface where you can reach your foot without rushing, dragging your skin, or improvising a transfer. If a transfer is involved, plan the sequence first, lock wheelchair brakes, and move footrests out of the way before movement. If transfer safety is uncertain, consult your healthcare provider.</li>
    <li><strong>Set your cushion-edge position.</strong> If you are working from the chair, scoot only as far forward as you can control without losing pelvic stability. Keep wheel locks engaged if your chair has them. Bring one leg into reach at a time, using the setup that already belongs to your daily routine (leg lifter, caregiver assist, transfer surface, or foot support).</li>
    <li><strong>Fold or bunch the sock before it touches your foot.</strong> Work the sock down into a shorter, controlled opening so the toe and heel go on first. Once the toes are seated and the heel pocket is aligned, pull gradually from the lower sock instead of yanking from the top cuff. If you are using DonnEase™ socks, the blue dot on toe always faces up, the #3 marker labeled PULL TO ANKLE is the first grip point, and the #2 marker labeled PULL TO KNEE is the second grip point.</li>
    <li><strong>Secure the cuff without leaving a ridge.</strong> After the heel is seated, work the fabric up the calf in small pulls. Smooth wrinkles as you go. A cuff that is rolled, folded, or bunched can become a friction spot later, especially near a brace edge, leg-rest tube, or calf support.</li>
    <li><strong>Repeat the same sequence on the second leg.</strong> The second side is often harder because fatigue has already started. Reset before you begin. Recheck the chair position, leg position, and sock orientation instead of forcing the last pull from a weaker angle.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Pressure-point safety for wheelchair users</h2>

  <p>The sock is only part of the system. After both socks are on, check where the fabric meets the wheelchair.</p>

  <p>Footplates can press against toes, heels, or the front of the sock. Calf supports can rub the back of the leg. Leg-rest hardware can catch a seam or cuff edge. Braces, splints, straps, and shoe openings can create smaller friction spots that are easy to miss when sensation is reduced.</p>

  <p>Use a fit-and-friction check, not a rigid cuff-height rule. Smooth wrinkles. Check the heel pocket. Look for fabric trapped under the foot or folded against equipment. Make sure the cuff is not sitting in the same line as a hard edge if you can reposition it comfortably.</p>

  <p>Skin-integrity sources warn that friction and shearing can matter for people with reduced mobility or reduced sensation. In this article, that means paying attention to comfort, fabric placement, and repeat contact points against equipment. If you notice persistent redness, blistering, skin breakdown, or a new mark you cannot feel clearly, consult your healthcare provider.</p>

  <p>If grip is the limiting factor, adaptive design may help. The <a href="/learn/donnease-adaptive-compression-guide">DonnEase™ adaptive compression guide</a> explains the wider opening, orientation marker, and pull markers in more detail.</p>

  <h2>Donning with a walker (sit-to-stand support)</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Set the walker before you start.</strong> Use a firm chair with armrests when possible. Place the walker close enough for the stand, with all tips or wheels grounded. If your walker has brakes, lock them. Do not start the sock while half-standing or leaning into an unstable frame.</li>
    <li><strong>Put most of the sock on while seated.</strong> Bring one foot into reach, fold or bunch the sock, seat the toes and heel, then work the fabric above the ankle. This seated portion is where most of the work should happen because both hands can focus on the sock without asking the walker to do the job of a chair.</li>
    <li><strong>Stand only after stable support is set.</strong> If you need to stand briefly for the final cuff adjustment, stand from the chair using armrests or handrails, not by pulling on or tilting the walker. Once upright, wait until you are steady before touching the sock. Then make the smallest cuff adjustment needed.</li>
    <li><strong>Return seated and check the fabric.</strong> Sit back down before detailed smoothing. Check the cuff, heel, and back of the calf for wrinkles or bunching. If you are using a brace or shoe with the walker, check the sock again after the shoe or brace is on.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>If you recently had hip surgery or have bending, crossing, or standing-dressing restrictions, follow the instructions from your surgeon, therapist, or discharge plan. Those restrictions can change the safest donning posture. When in doubt, consult your healthcare provider.</p>

  <h2>Donning with a cane (seated-edge approach)</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Start seated, with the cane within reach.</strong> A cane is for light support, balance, and stability during movement. It is not a stable donning platform. Sit at the edge of a bed or in a firm chair, ideally one with armrests, and keep the cane where you can reach it before standing.</li>
    <li><strong>Bring one foot into a controlled position.</strong> Use the posture you can maintain without twisting or rushing. Some cane users can cross one ankle over the opposite knee. Others need a footstool, reacher, caregiver assist, or sock aid. If a movement is restricted by surgery, pain, or balance, consult your healthcare provider.</li>
    <li><strong>Put the sock on while seated.</strong> Fold or bunch the sock, seat the toes, align the heel, then pull the fabric upward in stages. Smooth the ankle area before moving higher. The ankle is where graduated compression is firmest, so forcing the cuff from the top usually makes the job harder.</li>
    <li><strong>Stand only if a final adjustment requires it.</strong> Use the chair arms or other stable support to rise, then use the cane for balance once standing. If you are learning a new setup, having a helper nearby can be appropriate. Finish the smallest adjustment possible, then sit again for a fuller wrinkle check.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>When to ask for help, caregiver and OT guidance</h2>

  <p>There is no extra credit for turning sock donning into a solo test. If the task costs too much energy, creates unsafe transfers, or leaves marks you cannot monitor well, the setup needs to change.</p>

  <p>Occupational therapy is built for this category of problem. Dressing is an activity of daily living. Adaptive equipment, caregiver training, fall-prevention setup, home safety, and practical routines all belong in the conversation. An OT can look at your actual chair, walker, cane, bed height, hand function, balance, shoes, braces, and caregiver availability instead of giving generic instructions.</p>

  <p>Ask for help sooner if you cannot reach your foot without losing balance, cannot clear the heel without excessive pulling, cannot smooth wrinkles, cannot see or feel contact points, or need to combine sock donning with a transfer you do not fully control. Caregiver help is not failure. It is part of a safer routine when the mechanics demand another set of hands.</p>

  <p>If someone helps you, make the process specific. Decide where the sock starts, who lifts the leg, who checks the heel, who smooths the cuff, and who checks equipment contact after shoes, braces, or footplates are back in place. The <a href="/learn/caregiver-guide-compression-socks">caregiver guide for compression socks</a> is the better next read for that shared routine.</p>

